1. Overview
    The Customer key is an RSA-3072 key, generated by the customer. For CC312 compatibility, the key must
    have an exponent value of 0x10001 (65537). The customer key used by YOCTO Project® is fetched via the
    ‘hailo-secureboot-assets’ recipe located in ‘meta-hailo-bsp/recipes-bsp/hailo-secureboot-assets/hailosecureboot-assets.bb’. By default, the recipe fetches and deploys the development keypair and
    development certificate chain. The keys are then used by the various signing recipes (U-Boot SPL, u-boottfa, kernel) which depend on the ‘hailo-secureboot-assets recipe’ deploying the keys.
    The key generation and signing process involves:
    1. Generate customer key pair.
    2. Extract customer public key.
    3. Send over the public key to Hailo to be signed.
    4. Get signed certificate chain from Hailo.
    5. Create bitbake override file to generate signatures using the customer key OR perform signing manually when not using Yocto.

2. Key Generation and Signing Process
    An example of a key generation procedure using OpenSSL from a Linux terminal is:
        openssl genrsa -out customer_keypair.pem 3072
    This will generate an RSA-3072 key pair (private + public) file named customer_keypair.pem.

    To generate a .pem format public key from the key pair using openssl, run:
        openssl rsa -in customer_keypair.pem -out customer_pubkey.pem -pubout
    This will generate a ‘customer_pubkey.pem’ file containing the public key only.
    
    For the generation of the customer certificate binary by Hailo, Hailo requires the customer’s public key, in
    pem format – the same as the customer_pubkey.pem mentioned above.
